Introduction

This dataset comprises job postings from prominent companies such as Google and YouTube, offering detailed information about various job roles. Key attributes include job titles, categories, locations, responsibilities, and the required qualifications. By examining these attributes, the dataset provides valuable insights into the types of skills, educational backgrounds, and experiences that are highly sought after by employers in industries ranging from technology and media to consulting and operations.

Additionally, analyzing this dataset can help uncover trends in job requirements, such as the growing demand for technical skills like data analysis, software development, and cloud computing, as well as soft skills like leadership and collaboration. It also sheds light on the qualifications that improve employability, such as advanced degrees (e.g., Masters or Ph.D.), professional certifications, and practical hands-on experience.

For job seekers, this data serves as a guide to tailoring resumes and applications to meet market expectations. Employers, on the other hand, can use this data to benchmark their hiring requirements against industry standards and adjust their recruitment strategies to attract top talent. The dataset is also an excellent resource for researchers and educators aiming to align academic programs with current industry needs, ensuring that graduates are equipped with the skills required in a rapidly evolving job market.

# Re-import libraries
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from collections import Counter
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
import string


# Combine all qualifications into a single list
all_qualifications = Job_skills_data["Minimum Qualifications"].astype(str).tolist() + Job_skills_data["Preferred Qualifications"].astype(str).tolist()

# Preprocess the text data: lowercase, remove punctuation, and split into words
stop_words = set(stopwords.words("english"))
preprocessed_qualifications = [
    word.lower().strip(string.punctuation)
    for text in all_qualifications
    for word in text.split()
    if word.lower() not in stop_words and word not in string.punctuation
]

# Count the most common words/phrases
word_counts = Counter(preprocessed_qualifications)
top_skills = word_counts.most_common(10)

# Convert to DataFrame for visualization
skills_df = pd.DataFrame(top_skills, columns=["Skill/Qualification", "Count"])

# Plot the most common skills and qualifications
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.barh(skills_df["Skill/Qualification"], skills_df["Count"], color="skyblue")
plt.xlabel("Frequency", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.ylabel("Skills & Qualifications", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.title("Top 10 Most Relevant Skills & Qualifications in Job Postings", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Invert to show highest at the top
plt.show()

# Re-import libraries for analysis
import pandas as pd
from collections import Counter
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
import string



# Preprocessing function for text data
def preprocess_text(text_list):
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words("english"))
    cleaned_words = [
        word.lower().strip(string.punctuation)
        for text in text_list
        for word in text.split()
        if word.lower() not in stop_words and word not in string.punctuation
    ]
    return cleaned_words

# Process minimum and preferred qualifications
min_qualifications = Job_skills_data["Minimum Qualifications"].astype(str).tolist()
pref_qualifications = Job_skills_data["Preferred Qualifications"].astype(str).tolist()

min_words = preprocess_text(min_qualifications)
pref_words = preprocess_text(pref_qualifications)

# Count the most common words in each category
min_counts = Counter(min_words).most_common(10)
pref_counts = Counter(pref_words).most_common(10)

# Convert to DataFrames for visualization
min_df = pd.DataFrame(min_counts, columns=["Skill/Qualification", "Count"])
pref_df = pd.DataFrame(pref_counts, columns=["Skill/Qualification", "Count"])

# Plot Minimum Qualifications
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.barh(min_df["Skill/Qualification"], min_df["Count"], color="lightblue")
plt.title("Top 10 Minimum Qualifications", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.xlabel("Frequency", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.ylabel("Skills & Qualifications", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.show()

# Plot Preferred Qualifications
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.barh(pref_df["Skill/Qualification"], pref_df["Count"], color="lightgreen")
plt.title("Top 10 Preferred Qualifications", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
plt.xlabel("Frequency", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.ylabel("Skills & Qualifications", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.show()

display(Markdown('''### Key Differences Between Minimum and Preferred Qualifications Across Roles
The distinction between minimum and preferred qualifications reveals how employers differentiate between essential and desirable attributes for candidates:

Minimum Qualifications: These represent the essential requirements for a role, such as educational degrees (e.g., Bachelors in Computer Science or Engineering) and foundational skills (e.g., proficiency in Python, SQL, or Microsoft Office). These qualifications are typically non-negotiable and ensure that candidates possess the baseline capabilities required for the job.

Preferred Qualifications: These highlight additional desirable skills or experience that make a candidate stand out. Examples often include advanced degrees (e.g., Masters or MBA), specialized certifications (e.g., AWS, PMP), and extended experience in similar roles or industries. Soft skills like leadership, collaboration, and effective communication are also frequently listed as preferences.

Insights:
Preferred qualifications often align with leadership or strategic capabilities, whereas minimum qualifications focus on core technical skills and academic credentials.
The preferred category allows flexibility for employers to attract diverse candidates, while the minimum ensures a baseline competency.
This analysis helps job seekers understand how to prioritize developing their profiles, emphasizing meeting minimum qualifications while showcasing preferred skills to stand out.'''))

Key Differences Between Minimum and Preferred Qualifications Across Roles

The distinction between minimum and preferred qualifications reveals how employers differentiate between essential and desirable attributes for candidates:

Minimum Qualifications: These represent the essential requirements for a role, such as educational degrees (e.g., Bachelors in Computer Science or Engineering) and foundational skills (e.g., proficiency in Python, SQL, or Microsoft Office). These qualifications are typically non-negotiable and ensure that candidates possess the baseline capabilities required for the job.

Preferred Qualifications: These highlight additional desirable skills or experience that make a candidate stand out. Examples often include advanced degrees (e.g., Masters or MBA), specialized certifications (e.g., AWS, PMP), and extended experience in similar roles or industries. Soft skills like leadership, collaboration, and effective communication are also frequently listed as preferences.

Insights: Preferred qualifications often align with leadership or strategic capabilities, whereas minimum qualifications focus on core technical skills and academic credentials. The preferred category allows flexibility for employers to attract diverse candidates, while the minimum ensures a baseline competency. This analysis helps job seekers understand how to prioritize developing their profiles, emphasizing meeting minimum qualifications while showcasing preferred skills to stand out.

# Re-import necessary libraries
import pandas as pd
from collections import Counter
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Ensure Location and Minimum Qualifications columns contain strings and fill missing values
Job_skills_data["Location"] = Job_skills_data["Location"].astype(str).fillna("")
Job_skills_data["Minimum Qualifications"] = Job_skills_data["Minimum Qualifications"].astype(str).fillna("")

# Group by Location and combine minimum qualifications for each location
qualifications_by_location = Job_skills_data.groupby("Location")["Minimum Qualifications"].apply(lambda x: " ".join(x))

# Keywords to filter for analysis
keywords = ["experience", "degree", "equivalent", "practical", "years"]

# Function to count specific keywords in text data
def count_keywords(text_data, keywords):
    words = text_data.lower().split()
    keyword_counts = {keyword: words.count(keyword) for keyword in keywords}
    return keyword_counts

# Analyze keyword counts for the top 5 locations with the most job postings
top_locations = Job_skills_data["Location"].value_counts().head(5).index
keyword_counts_by_location = {location: count_keywords(qualifications_by_location[location], keywords) for location in top_locations}

# Convert the data to a DataFrame for easier visualization
keyword_counts_df = pd.DataFrame(keyword_counts_by_location).T

# Plot the comparison of keywords across locations
keyword_counts_df.plot(kind="bar", figsize=(12, 6), colormap="viridis")
plt.title("Comparison of Specific Qualifications Across Top Locations", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
plt.xlabel("Location", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.ylabel("Frequency", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend(title="Qualifications")
plt.grid(axis="y", linestyle="--", alpha=0.7)
plt.show()
